# Roster Tracker

A live, team-shared dashboard that ingests your **Employee Basic export**
(First Name, Last Name, Employee Status Description, Position Job Title,
Employment Type Description, Hire Date, Company Name, Location Description,
Department Description), and:

- Flags who's **new** or **departed** since the last upload (matched by
  name — see the caveat below).
- Flags anyone whose status changed (e.g. moved to **Leave of Absence**).
- Flags anyone who **moved locations**.
- Groups staff by role/location in the same tracker-style tabbed view you
  already use, instead of a manual census-band grid (this export doesn't
  carry band assignments, so grouping by role is the closest equivalent —
  see "How the roster view differs" below).
- Lets you set **current census** and **ratio** per location (not in this
  export, so it's a small editable field that persists across uploads) and
  raises alerts when RN/Aide coverage is approaching or has exceeded that
  ratio.
- Auto-fills an **Actual hires per month** row from each employee's Hire
  Date — e.g. 3 RNs hired in June shows up as a 3 under June automatically.
  **Planned** hiring stays editable, since that's a forward-looking target,
  not something in the data.

Runs entirely on Netlify: a static dashboard + one serverless function +
Netlify Blobs for shared storage. No database to provision, no extra
accounts.

## How it works

- **You upload the Employee Basic export**, 2–3x/week, right from the
  dashboard. Parsing happens in the browser — the raw file is never sent
  anywhere, only the structured employee list.
- That list is POSTed to a Netlify Function, which compares it to the
  **last stored snapshot** (shared across your team via Netlify Blobs),
  works out who's new, who dropped off, who moved locations, and whose
  status changed — then stores the new snapshot + a running history log.
- Anyone who opens the dashboard, on any device, sees the same live data.

## How the roster view differs from the original mock-up

The original roster workbook had a manual **census-band grid** (who's
assigned to patients numbered 1–10, 11–20, etc.). The Employee Basic export
doesn't carry that assignment info — it only has name, position,
department, location, employment type, status, and hire date. So instead
of a band grid, staff are grouped **by role** (e.g. all RN Case Managers at
a location, together, with active/leave/total counts) — same "who's
covering this location" purpose, just built from data that's actually in
this file.

Employment Type = "As Needed" is treated as PRN staff. Department =
"Administrative" is treated as admin roles. Everything else clinical is
grouped by role.

## Known limitation: name matching

This export has no employee ID column, so people are matched by first +
last name. If two employees ever share an exact name, the diff could
mismatch them. Worth watching for; adding an ID column to future exports
(if your system can produce one) would make this exact.

## What it expects from your Excel file

A single sheet with these column headers (exact text, case-insensitive):
`First Name`, `Last Name`, `Employee Status Description`, `Position Job
Title`, `Employment Type Description`, `Hire Date`, `Company Name`,
`Location Description`, `Department Description`. If your export ever
renames a column, update `HEADER_MAP` in `public/index.html`.

## Deploying it

Drag-and-drop deploys don't run serverless functions properly, so use one
of these:

### Option A — GitHub + Netlify (recommended)
1. Create a new GitHub repo and push this whole folder to it.
2. In Netlify: **Add new site → Import an existing project → GitHub** →
   pick the repo.
3. Netlify reads `netlify.toml` automatically (publish dir `public`,
   functions dir `netlify/functions`). Click **Deploy**.
4. Netlify Blobs works automatically on any deployed Netlify site — no
   extra setup.

### Option B — Netlify CLI from your machine
```bash
npm install -g netlify-cli
cd roster-tracker
netlify deploy --prod
```

Either way, you'll get a URL like `https://your-site-name.netlify.app` —
share that with your team.

## Using it day to day

1. Open the dashboard URL.
2. Type your name in "Uploaded by".
3. Choose the latest Employee Basic `.xlsx` export.
4. The dashboard updates for everyone within seconds — new/departed staff,
   status changes, and moves show up in the Changes panel; the tracker
   view and hiring grid refresh.
5. On a location tab, set **Current census** / **Ratio** and click Save
   the first time (or whenever it changes) to enable that location's
   alerts. Set **Planned hiring** per month the same way.

## Where to take this next

- **Email alerts**: add a Netlify **Scheduled Function** (cron-based) that
  reuses `computeAlerts()` from `roster.mjs` on a timer and sends email via
  a provider like Resend or SendGrid when something crosses a threshold.
- **Per-location ratio rules**: right now RN and Aide are the only
  departments checked against ratio. Extending to other departments (On
  Call Nurse, etc.) is a small change to `computeAlerts()`.
- **Employee ID matching**: if your HR system can export a unique ID,
  swapping the diff key from name to ID removes the same-name risk noted
  above.
- **Census history / trend charts**: the history log already stores every
  upload's diff; snapshotting census over time would let you chart trends.

## Files

```
roster-tracker/
├─ netlify.toml                    # build + function config
├─ package.json                    # @netlify/blobs dependency
├─ netlify/functions/roster.mjs    # backend: diffing, storage, alerts, hiring tally
├─ netlify/functions/settings.mjs  # backend: census/ratio/planned-hiring storage
└─ public/index.html               # dashboard: upload, parsing, all rendering
```
